ce:section.ce:para:
C. jejuni NCTC11168, S. aureus, and L. 
monocytogenes were irradiated with LED at wavelengths of 425 nm, 565 nm, and 700 nm, to determine the wavelength that resulted in optimal antibacterial effects. The results showed that C. jejuni NCTC11168 cell counts decreased in only 1 h at a wavelength of 425 nm (Fig. 1
), but there was no significant antibacterial effect on the other bacteria (data not shown). Therefore, N-CNDs were added to the enrichment broth at 20 mg/mL and irradiated with LED at 425 nm. The results showed that C. jejuni NCTC11168 cell counts decreased significantly after 60 min LED irradiation at 425 nm. However, addition of the N-CNDs without irradiation did not reduce the cell counts significantly after 60 min (Fig. 2
). Hence, the optimal irradiation time was determined to be 1 h, and the optimal concentration of N-CNDs was further examined. When C. jejuni NCTC11168 were irradiated with LED at 425 nm for 1 h in Bolton broth containing N-CNDs at 0.1 to 20 mg/mL, the cell counts did not decrease at more than 5 mg/mL of N-CNDs and a significant increase in C. jejuni NCTC11168 cell counts was observed at more than 10 mg/mL of N-CNDs after the LED irradiation (Fig. 3
). During the enrichment for C. jejuni detection, the growth of competitive bacteria such as A. baumannii hindered subsequent detection. Other studies (Line et al., 2008; Yoo et al., 2014) have shown that the detection efficiency of Campylobacter decreased in the presence of A. baumannii. Hence, the control of A. baumannii is important for the detection of C. jejuni. To control A. baumannii in this study, N-CNDs (0.1–20 mg/mL) mixed with A. baumannii were irradiated with LED at 425 nm for 1 h. The results showed that the antimicrobial activity of N-CNDs was higher at concentrations of 5 mg/mL (Fig. 4
). This result indicates that more than 5 mg/mL of N-CNDs can destroy A. baumannii during 1 h LED irradiation at 425 nm. However, the significant increase C. jejuni NCTC11168 cell counts was observed at more than 10 mg/mL of N-CNDs. Thus, 10 mg/mL of N-CNDs was chosen as an appropriate concentration of N-CNDs. After adding 10 mg/mL of N-CNDs and irradiation at 425 nm of LED for 60 min, the cell counts of A. baumannii, S. aureus, and L. monocytogenes were enumerated. The result showed that 1.5 log CFU/mL of mean was inhibited in the N-CNDs added group (Fig. 5
). The N-CNDs synthesized in this study can generate heat and acoustic waves when exposed to light (Lee et al., 2016). Thus, unlike C. jejuni NCTC11168 cell counts, A. baumannii cell counts decreased when irradiated at 425 nm in a mixture containing N-CNDs. It can be assumed that N-CNDs adhere to A. baumannii cells and may kill the bacteria by the photothermal effect. After the irradiation of N-CNDs-supplemented Bolton broth at 425 nm for 1 h, enrichment was conducted for 24 h. The quantification results showed that C. jejuni NCTC11168 cell counts in N-CNDs-supplemented Bolton broth were 100 times higher than those in Bolton broth alone (Fig. 6A), but the enrichment of A. baumannii was 10 times lesser in N-CNDs treatments (Fig. 6B). These results suggest that a combination of N-CNDs (10 mg/mL) and 1 h LED irradiation at 425 nm allowed better C. jejuni growth during enrichment by destroying other bacteria. Even though the morphology of C. jejuni is rod, it has spiral shape. In addition, C. jejuni has corkscrew-like mobility, and the cell size is smaller than those of the other bacteria (Hou et al., 2018). These factors may allow less N-CNDs attachment on the cell surface than other bacteria. This difference may induce better survival for C. jejuni from the photothermal reaction of N-CNDs than the other bacteria.

More than 20 hybridoma cells were obtained. Among these, cells producing antibodies with high specificity and potency were selected, and cross-reactivity with other bacteria was examined using ID-ELISA. The results showed that the hybridomas (H10–17, H10–18, H10–36, and H10–49) obtained in this study had high specificity against C. jejuni NCTC11168 (Fig. 7
                        ). In addition, titer measurement using the supernatant from the selected hybridoma cells showed that the detection sensitivity was 5 log CFU/mL. The concentration of antibody was the highest in H10–36, and a 1000-fold dilution was appropriate for C. jejuni NCTC11168 detection (Fig. 8
                        ). In poultry products, the contamination level is usually 2 log CFU/g (Lee et al., 2017). Therefore, to use this antibody with a 5 log CFU/mL detection limit, the samples must be enriched to increase the bacterial cell counts up to 5 log CFU/mL. However, even though the bacteria were enriched up to 5 log CFU/mL, it was difficult to detect the target bacteria because other bacteria were also enriched, and therefore, they disrupted the detection. Thus, addition of N-CNDs before enrichment may solve this problem for C. jejuni detection.
